#2023SBR Q12
Hypertrophic myopathy = genetical determined LVH.
Hypertrophy of the LEFT VENTRICLE can have varying morphologies -> leading to varying haemodynamic effects and clinical features:

[!TIP] Think hypertrophied, misshapen ventricle

Haemodynamic effects :

  1. LVOTO - outflow obstruction
  2. Diastolic dysfunction
  3. Myocardial ischemia
  4. Mitral regurgitation - papillary muscle or chordae abnormalities.
  5. increased risk of supra ventricular and ventricular arrhythmias.

Symptoms: palpitation, chest pain, sudden cardiac death, syncope (particularly during or immediately following exertion) , exertional dyspnoea,

Auscultation: systolic murmurs of LV obstruction and mitral regurgitation.
Echo - hyperdynamic, small, underfilled VL.

Management of HOCM

management of patient with obstruction

  • avoid dehydration
  • Avoid treatment reducing preload OR afterload.
  • Drugs which could worsen obstruction:
    • Nifedipine and amlodipine - reduced afterload?
    • Nitroglycerin - ?beware in presentation with angina
    • Arterial vasodilators, such as ACEi and ARB
    • Digoxin - ?increased contractility?
    • Frusemide - reduced preload
  • If asymptomatic, not medication neded.
  • If symptomatic, first line -> beta blocker; if not working, verapamil or diltiazem. (nondihydropiridines)
  • Surgical resection or alcohol ablation for refractory cases?

management of patients without obstruction

  • some minor details in management; more or less not special treatment needed unless their are haemodynamic / symptomatic effects.

Essential / primary hypertension

  • 90% of hypertensives have Primary hypertension - i.e no identifiable cause.
    • BP is influenced by many genes. Each one has a tiny effect on it's own.
    • Specially in this group, diet and lifetyle have definite influences on blood pressure

There are various mechanisms described for the development of hypertension which includes 

  • increased salt absorption resulting in volume expansion,
  • an impaired response of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS),
  • increased activation of the sympathetic nervous system.
  • These changes lead to the development of increased total peripheral resistance and increased afterload which in turn leads to the development of hypertension.
    Source

The multifactorial pathogenesis of essential hypertension is described more here: See the headings.
[[pathophysiologyEssentialHypertension.pdf]]

Kidney transplants from hypertensive patients induce hypertension in the recipient and transplants from normotensive donors reduce BP in hypertensive patients - This shows the close relationship between kidneys and blood pressure regulation. - Rang and Dale's Pharmacology.

Secondary hypertension

  • 10% of patients have Secondary hypertension - (higher proportion in those < 30 years old)
    • Commonest causes of secondary hypertension are
      1. Primary Hyperaldoesteronism - increased circulatory volume
      2. Obstrucive sleep apnoea
      3. Obesity
      • Obesity and OSA cause increased sympathetic tone. Leptin secreted by adipocytes has a sympathetic stimulatory activity.
    • Other causes of secondary hypertension
      • Pregnancy - usually BP drops in #pregnancy (Volume↑, but tone ↓↓ = lower BP) but some patients have PIH and pre-eclampsia.
      • Renal - renal artery stenosis, CKD
      • Vascular - Coarcation of aorta
      • Neural - autonomic dysfunction
      • Endocrine - ↑ Aldosterone, ↓ Cortisol, Phaechromocytoma, Hypo And Hyper thyroidism, Acromegaly

Why isn't there compensatory bradycardia in patients with hypertension?

Blocks of the sodium-chloride (Na/Cl) channel in the proximal segment of the DCT; Reduces at most 3-5% of Na Reabsorption because that's all the DCT does. Therefore, not as powerful as other diuretics. But achieves enough diuresis for control of hypertension.
Increases Ca resorption because of increased Na flux through Na/Ca transported. Increased Na delivery to CD -> increased loss of K+

[!INFO] Basis of BP reduction
A small reduction in BP (10mmHg SBP and 5mmHg of DBP) has huge benefits -> 20% reduction in MI, 35% stroke, 40% HF etc!

lifestyle modification

Very important: lifestyle changes produce complementary reductions in BP comparable to pharmacotherapy. Recommended FOR ALL PATIENTS

Most side effects of antihypertensives are dose dependent [[General Medicine 1#Q 18 Drug side effects]]. So lower doses of a combination may be less harmful than high dose of a single drug.

Older / black people - lower renin levels -> lower effectiveness of RAAS blockade.
Younger white people - higher renin -> RAAS blockade is more effective.

Preeclampsia

Offer labetalol to treat hypertension in pregnant women with pre-eclampsia. Offer nifedipine[3] for women in whom labetalol is not suitable, and methyldopa if labetalol or nifedipine[3] are not suitable.

Management of hypertension in post partum period

#2023SBR Q3
Can use enalapril with monitoring of renal function and pottasium.
Avoid diuretics and ARBs in post partum period.
Avoid methyldopa as it carries risk of depression.

Direct oral anticoagulants - DOACs - are now preffered over warfarin. Less risk of bleeing.

DOACs

Source
#2023SBR Q10
DOACs = novel anti coagulants = non vitamin K oral anticoagulants
VKAs inhibit synthesis of vitamin K depencent factors.
DOACs - "direct" - directly inhibit some proteins in the clotting cascade.

Dabigatran -> Thrombin inhibitor
Rivaroxaban, apixaban and edoxaban -> the factor Xa inhibitors,

Advantages over VKA:
More predictable rise of INR - administered at fixed dose and do not need monitoring.
Fewer interactions.
rapid onset and short half-lives - no need for periprocedural bridging.

Disadvantages:
Reversing agents not readily available - except for idarucizumab for dabigatran;
renal impairment required dose adjustment.
Dabigatran crosses the placenta: avoid in #pregnancy

Contraindications for DOAC (i.e Use VKA)

  • prosthetic valve
  • Significant mitral stenosis
  • Bioprosthetic valve placement within 3 - months.
  • patients on drugs causing interactions with DOACs.

Relative contraindications (may need a VKA)

  • patient is not likely to comply with twice daily dosing of DOACs.
  • eGFR < 30.

They should NOT be used for thromboprophylaxis in patients with mechanical heart valves.
RE-ALIGN #study showed increased risk of thrombosis.

Definition of hypertension

AHA guidelines . SBP > 130 , DBP > 80
European : SBP > 140, DBP > 90.
Based on average of two or more readings taken at two or more visits.
BP cuff should cover 80% of the upper arm.

Management of primary polycythemia

#2023SBR Q9
Goals of care

  1. reduce symptoms
  2. reduce risk of thrombosis -> phlebotomy to keep HCT < 45% + aspirin for all patients
    1. Cytoreductive therapy with hydroxyurea for high risk patients (age > 60 or with history of thrombosis) or those with refractory symptoms.
      1. Inhibits ribonucleotide reductase that interferes with DNA repair. It is effective at lowering platelet counts.
    2. Busulfan or interferon alpha are possible alternative therapies.
  3. prevent progression to leukemic transformation or [[Cytopaenias#Myelofibrosis| myelofibrosis]] or acute myeloid leukemia.

Weakness accentuated by rest! and cold

[[2022-November#Complement system overview]]

Afferent limbs projec to Nucleus of tractus solitarius -> excitatory projections to vagal nucleus AND GABAergic inhibitory projections to sympathetic centers.
RVLM centers are stimulated by hypoxia and hypercapnia -> which occurs in decreased cerebral perfusion due to increased intracranial pressure. Increased RVLM discharge then causes the Cushing's reflex. (increased BP stimulates the aortic barroreceptors -> bradycardia)
